{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511859"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:46:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:46:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11808"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11808"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.07,0.03,0.85,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4413"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88133"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4413"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11808"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72324"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3073"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6264"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6511"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9768"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9826"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14961"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30015"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88133"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her husband due to changes in her mood over the past three months. She appears hesitant to discuss her symptoms. Her husband reports she has become increasingly withdrawn and irritable, with disrupted sleep and reduced interest in previously enjoyed activities. She has also stopped driving and using public transport. She works from home as a graphic designer but her productivity has declined. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears anxious but maintains good eye contact. When asked about recent stressors, she mentions a motor vehicle accident just over three months ago where she sustained minor physical injuries. Further questioning reveals occasional intrusive memories of the accident, accompanied by palpitations and sweating. Her husband notes she often wakes up distressed in the middle of the night. She becomes tearful when describing how she deliberately takes longer routes to avoid busy intersections. She denies thoughts of self-harm or suicide.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adjustment disorder","Acute stress disorder","Major depressive disorder (MDD)","Post-traumatic stress disorder","Dissociative amnesia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms following a motor vehicle accident that occurred three months ago. The clinical picture shows classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003Epost-traumatic stress disorder\u003C/strong\u003E, including re-experiencing phenomena (intrusive memories with physiological reactions like palpitations and sweating), avoidance behaviours (stopping driving, avoiding busy intersections), and hyperarousal symptoms (sleep disturbance, irritability). The symptoms have persisted for more than three months, significantly impacting her daily functioning and work productivity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdjustment disorder\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered given her mood changes and functional decline following the accident. However, the specific trauma-related symptoms (intrusive memories, physiological arousal, and marked avoidance) are more severe than would be expected in adjustment disorder, which typically presents with more generalised emotional or behavioural symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute stress disorder\u003C/strong\u003E presents with similar symptoms but is diagnosed only in the first month following trauma. The three-month duration since the accident excludes this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMajor depressive disorder\u003C/strong\u003E could appear to fit given her withdrawal, reduced interest, and impact on functioning. However, while depressive symptoms may be present, the prominent trauma-specific symptoms (intrusive memories, physiological arousal to triggers, and specific avoidance of driving-related situations) point more strongly to PTSD as the primary diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDissociative amnesia\u003C/strong\u003E involves inability to recall important autobiographical information. While this patient shows avoidance of trauma-related triggers, she clearly remembers the accident and experiences intrusive recollections rather than memory loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe case demonstrates how PTSD can present initially with non-specific symptoms of mood change and social withdrawal, but careful history reveals the characteristic triad of re-experiencing, avoidance, and hyperarousal symptoms related to a specific traumatic event.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Post-traumatic stress disorder can present with subtle symptoms that may be mistaken for depression or anxiety","The presence of re-experiencing phenomena, avoidance behaviours, and hyperarousal symptoms are key diagnostic features of PTSD","Duration of symptoms greater than one month distinguishes PTSD from acute stress disorder"],"references":["Carta, M.G., Balestrieri, M., Murru, A. et al. Adjustment Disorder: epidemiology, diagnosis and treatment. Clin Pract Epidemiol Ment Health 5, 15 (2009). https://doi.org/10.1186/1745-0179-5-15","Zelviene P, Kazlauskas E. Adjustment disorder: current perspectives. Neuropsychiatr Dis Treat. 2018 Jan 25;14:375-381. doi: 10.2147/NDT.S121072. PMID: 29416339; PMCID: PMC5790100."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72324"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11808"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/72324"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-02T10:15:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-02T10:17:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4413"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88133"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji